2
00:00:04.030 --> 00:00:08.050
It's all right! It's time to move on

3
00:00:08.310 --> 00:00:11.590
The sun shines always in our hearts

4
00:00:11.730 --> 00:00:15.010
Hand in hand, we convey our power

5
00:00:15.100 --> 00:00:18.680
And make our wishes come true

6
00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:32.490
Combining our strengths, we'll crest these surging seas

7
00:00:33.750 --> 00:00:40.290
Hurry toward the thrill of danger—
Let the adventure begin!

8
00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:47.130
Now's the time to set sail; raise the anchor

9
00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:55.010
Off to the seas of adventure, through rainbow-colored winds

10
00:00:55.060 --> 00:00:58.550
Our journey's fraught with injury

11
00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:02.270
But what we cherish most is right at our side

12
00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:06.350
And if you get into a jam

13
00:01:06.450 --> 00:01:08.360
I'll always be there to protect you

14
00:01:09.450 --> 00:01:13.360
It's all right! It's time to move on

15
00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:16.820
The sun shines always in our hearts

16
00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:20.330
Shoulder to shoulder, we face all coming storms

17
00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:24.200
And look to the future for the light of hope

18
00:01:24.670 --> 00:01:27.920
If we gather up the pieces of our dreams

19
00:01:28.390 --> 00:01:31.550
They'll make a chart leading to tomorrow

20
00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:34.720
We come together under the same Jolly Roger

21
00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:40.450
And make our wishes come true; together, we are...

22
00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:54.170
<b>The City of Water, Water Seven</b>

23
00:01:54.310 --> 00:02:00.890
Luffy and Robin needed to recover, so the Going Merry
remained anchored off the uninhabited island for four days.

24
00:02:00.890 --> 00:02:05.850
After that, we set sail, and now this is
the third morning since we resumed our voyage.

25
00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:08.690
Today's weather is a gorgeous mix of spring...

26
00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:11.310
and occasional bouts of summer.

27
00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:18.490
What a beautiful day!

28
00:02:19.090 --> 00:02:22.490
Nami my sweet!

29
00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:30.290
I made pomme paille.
Mademoiselle, if you would...

30
00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:34.100
Mmm, it's delicious!

31
00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:36.680
I'm overjoyed!

32
00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:39.470
Keep it down! I'm trying to sleep!

33
00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:43.000
Yeah, yeah... Sorry about that, cactus head.

34
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.310
What'd you say, dartboard brows?!

35
00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:47.950
Dar– Did I hear you right, you bastard?!

36
00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:50.000
Dartboard brows.

37
00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:57.610
Luffy! Yeah! Luffy! All right!

38
00:02:57.610 --> 00:03:02.230
Luffy! Yeah! Luffy!

39
00:03:04.430 --> 00:03:06.980
Finally!

40
00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:06.980
Luffy!

41
00:03:13.790 --> 00:03:16.750
This is my frozen-self reenactment.

42
00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:27.890
The heck...? I can't believe he's doing that
after he got frozen and almost died.

43
00:03:29.740 --> 00:03:30.730
Was it close?

44
00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:33.480
You nailed it! That was exactly it, Luffy!

45
00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:35.870
Clean that up good, okay, Luffy?!

46
00:03:35.870 --> 00:03:38.860
Hm...? Oh! What're you eating, Nami?

47
00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:41.140
It's paille, a potato dish.

48
00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:45.240
Potato, huh? I'm hungry too. Hey, Sanji!

49
00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:48.960
Just how much sleep do you need anyway?!

50
00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.210
How much sleep I "need" is
 my business! Let's settle this!

51
00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:06.300
They said this is called paille. It's good!

52
00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:08.580
What's paille?

53
00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:12.650
It's the tail meat of a huge
monster named Paille.

54
00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:16.190
I slew it, though. It was at least
a hundred meters tall.

55
00:04:16.800 --> 00:04:19.460
A hundred meters?! That's amazing, Usopp!

56
00:04:19.460 --> 00:04:21.610
Yeah, and I did it all before breakfast.

57
00:04:21.610 --> 00:04:24.260
What? You got up early and killed it?

58
00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:27.490
Chopper, say my name.

59
00:04:27.490 --> 00:04:31.080
What? That's, of course, C-Captain...

60
00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:35.580
That's right! My name is Captain... Usopp–

61
00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:39.340
Robin!

62
00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:42.500
Hey! Robin my love!

63
00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:43.720
Robin!

64
00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:46.510
How are you feeling? Are you chilly?

65
00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:50.970
I'm feeling a lot better
all thanks to an amazing doctor.

66
00:04:50.970 --> 00:04:56.600
Oh, being called an amazing doctor won't
make me feel happy or anything, you jerk.

67
00:04:56.600 --> 00:04:58.440
He sure does look happy.

68
00:04:57.560 --> 00:04:58.440
Yeah.

69
00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:00.270
Take it easy, Robin.

70
00:05:00.270 --> 00:05:05.170
Don't feel pressured just because Luffy is up
and about after experiencing the same thing.

71
00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:07.160
It's okay to take your time and rest.

72
00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:09.160
– Yay! 
– That wasn't a compliement!

73
00:05:09.730 --> 00:05:13.230
Robin! Shall I make something
to warm you up?

74
00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:14.540
How's your appetite?

75
00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:16.210
Well...

76
00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.300
may I have some coffee?

77
00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:21.030
Absolutely! It'll be my pleasure!

78
00:05:35.690 --> 00:05:36.850
Hm?

79
00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:38.650
What's that?

80
00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:50.260
Anyway, this paille thing is so good
that we can't stop eating it.

81
00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:52.000
Yeah, it's yummy!

82
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.040
How much would we make if we sold this?

83
00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:55.370
Hey, Luffy!

84
00:05:55.370 --> 00:05:58.300
A f-f-frog is doing the front crawl!

85
00:05:58.300 --> 00:05:59.460
What?

86
00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:01.480
It went to your side, so take a look!

87
00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:02.380
Is that true?

88
00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:04.380
A frog...? Could it be that frog?

89
00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:09.470
Hey, Luffy, are you seriously taking stock
in what that dumb admiral said?

90
00:06:09.470 --> 00:06:11.550
For starters, a frog could never do the–

91
00:06:11.550 --> 00:06:14.310
It's doing it! A-A frog is doing the front crawl!

92
00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:16.150
Let's follow it, guys!

93
00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:16.990
– Aye!
– Aye!

94
00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:20.800
Furl the sail! Stand by the oars!
Turn the ship to two o'clock!

95
00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:21.860
– Aye!
– Aye!

96
00:06:21.860 --> 00:06:22.890
Faster!

97
00:06:22.890 --> 00:06:26.280
I can't explain it, but I can't
fight the urge to go after it!

98
00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:29.280
Sorry to keep you waiting, mademoiselles.

99
00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:32.830
What the...?

100
00:06:32.830 --> 00:06:34.700
What?! What happened?!

101
00:06:37.800 --> 00:06:39.960
It feels like the ship changed course.

102
00:06:39.960 --> 00:06:44.420
Hey, you guys! Who said you could
change course without consulting me?!

103
00:06:44.420 --> 00:06:46.650
Hey, Nami, you've got to hear this!

104
00:06:46.650 --> 00:06:49.380
We found a huge frog
with scars all over its body!

105
00:06:50.100 --> 00:06:51.680
What the heck?

106
00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:55.240
The plan's to roast it whole and eat it!

107
00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:56.470
– You're gonna eat it?!
– You're gonna eat it?!

108
00:06:57.890 --> 00:06:59.250
Hey, you're right.

109
00:07:00.300 --> 00:07:02.480
Hm? Is that a lighthouse?

110
00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:08.150
Why is there a lighthouse all the way
out here? I wonder if someone's there...

111
00:07:08.150 --> 00:07:10.530
Wh-What do you see? Is it an island?

112
00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:14.870
No, it's a lighthouse. Log poses
shouldn't point to places like these.

113
00:07:14.870 --> 00:07:17.790
And the frog? Tell us
the direction the frog went!

114
00:07:17.790 --> 00:07:18.790
Not a chance!

115
00:07:18.790 --> 00:07:19.000
Not a chance! The frog is headed to the lighthouse.

116
00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.500
The frog is headed to the lighthouse.

117
00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:21.710
What? The frog is headed to the lighthouse.

118
00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:21.920
To cook frogs, first remove
the slime using white wine, What?

119
00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:25.170
To cook frogs, first remove
the slime using white wine,

120
00:07:25.170 --> 00:07:27.300
and then dredge them
in flour and fry them crisp.

121
00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:27.510
and then dredge them
in flour and fry them crisp. Hey, Sanji!

122
00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:28.800
Hey, Sanji!

123
00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:29.010
Hey, Sanji! If our captain says we're going,
what choice do we have but to go?

124
00:07:29.010 --> 00:07:33.220
If our captain says we're going,
what choice do we have but to go?

125
00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:33.430
Robin... If our captain says we're going,
what choice do we have but to go?

126
00:07:33.430 --> 00:07:35.180
Robin...

127
00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:38.240
All right! Full speed ahead!

128
00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:39.240
– Aye!
– Aye!

129
00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:41.140
What's with the solidarity?!

130
00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:44.980
– Heave-ho! Heave-ho! Heave-ho!
– Heave-ho! Heave-ho! Heave-ho!

131
00:07:49.900 --> 00:07:51.800
It's flying!

132
00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:55.240
Don't let it get away! Move ahead
of it and block its course!

133
00:07:55.240 --> 00:07:59.330
– Heave-ho! Heave-ho! Heave-ho!
– Heave-ho! Heave-ho! Heave-ho!

134
00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:13.880
We ran aground on something!

135
00:08:16.180 --> 00:08:19.390
Ah, Nami, Robin, are you two okay?

136
00:08:19.390 --> 00:08:21.990
Yeah, somehow...

137
00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:23.390
I'm okay.

138
00:08:24.420 --> 00:08:25.880
Thank goodness.

139
00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:30.150
What? What's that sound?

140
00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:32.860
What? What's going on?

141
00:08:48.370 --> 00:08:50.590
Is this...? Don't tell me...

142
00:08:58.350 --> 00:09:00.810
Why...? In a place like this...?!

143
00:09:00.810 --> 00:09:03.730
Ow, ow, ow!

144
00:09:05.550 --> 00:09:08.480
Go back! Go back! Rotate 180 degrees!

145
00:09:27.250 --> 00:09:29.210
What the hell is this?!

146
00:09:32.170 --> 00:09:34.800
Wh-Wh-What in the world
is this hulking piece of iron?!

147
00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:36.260
A ship?

148
00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:39.600
Impossible! Something shaped
like this isn't seaworthy!

149
00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:45.600
Hey, frog! Run! What're you doing?!

150
00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:56.900
Ah! It got run over!

151
00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:23.560
The ship was puffing out smoke!

152
00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:35.610
Pirates...?

153
00:10:35.610 --> 00:10:38.360
Grandma! Grandma! Pirates are here!

154
00:10:38.360 --> 00:10:41.740
What?! Is that so, Chimney?!

155
00:10:41.740 --> 00:10:45.280
Okay then, bring the transponder snail to me!

156
00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:46.000
Okay!

157
00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.120
This is a problem.
Someone came out of the building.

158
00:10:50.120 --> 00:10:52.080
They're gonna call for help.

159
00:10:53.250 --> 00:10:54.690
Here it is, Grandma!

160
00:10:54.690 --> 00:10:56.550
Um... Hello?

161
00:10:56.550 --> 00:11:01.210
Let's see... What was it? I forgot.

162
00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:02.510
She's wasted?!

163
00:11:07.470 --> 00:11:13.080
Oh? Paille, huh? It goes good with booze.

164
00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:15.440
Whoa! This is tasty!

165
00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:19.200
I'm Chimney. This is our cat, Gonbe,

166
00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:17.280
<b>Chimney
Kokoro's Grandchild</b>

167
00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:19.240
<b>Gonbe
A Cat (Actually a Rabbit)</b>

168
00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:20.690
and Grandma Kokoro.

169
00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:23.530
<b>Stationmaster Kokoro
Shift Station</b>

170
00:11:20.690 --> 00:11:24.830
You guys aren't train robbers, are you?

171
00:11:24.830 --> 00:11:27.700
I'm Luffy. I'm the man
who'll be King of the Pirates.

172
00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:28.420
Really?!

173
00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:29.000
Yeah.

174
00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:31.960
What a funny guy.

175
00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:34.790
Say, Chimney, that thing
is a steamship, right?

176
00:11:34.790 --> 00:11:39.030
But with a shape like that,
there's no way it could ever sail.

177
00:11:39.030 --> 00:11:41.170
Never seen nothin' like it, huh?

178
00:11:41.170 --> 00:11:43.720
This is the only place in the world it exists.

179
00:11:43.720 --> 00:11:47.160
It's a sea train called the Puffing Tom.

180
00:11:47.160 --> 00:11:48.680
Puffing Tom?

181
00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:52.190
A steam engine turns the paddle wheels
as it rides the sea railway.

182
00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:56.790
Railway?

183
00:11:56.790 --> 00:12:00.190
That's right. It floats
just below the water's surface.

184
00:12:00.190 --> 00:12:05.190
The train travels the same route every day,
taking passengers from one island to another.

185
00:12:05.190 --> 00:12:07.120
It also hauls ships and delivers mail.

186
00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:09.660
She's right. There really is a railway.

187
00:12:09.660 --> 00:12:12.500
Yup! There's both a signal and a partition.

188
00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:14.330
It's dangerous to cross the barrier!

189
00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:18.390
Dangerous or not,
that guy wouldn't understand, right?

190
00:12:18.390 --> 00:12:22.090
It wasn't nice to send him flying.
We were chasing him, you know.

191
00:12:22.090 --> 00:12:24.890
By "that guy," do you mean Yokozuna?

192
00:12:24.890 --> 00:12:26.990
Yep, that front-crawl frog.

193
00:12:26.990 --> 00:12:29.900
Yokozuna wouldn't die from that.

194
00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:33.090
He's the source of all our
headaches here at Shift Station.

195
00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:36.700
He loves testing his strength
by trying to defeat the sea train.

196
00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:38.180
He'll be back.

197
00:12:38.180 --> 00:12:42.120
Testing his strength? Oh!
That's why he stood his ground, huh?

198
00:12:42.120 --> 00:12:43.720
He's sure got guts.

199
00:12:43.720 --> 00:12:46.370
Give me a break! He's a royal pain!

200
00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:49.450
The grill also keeps getting broken!

201
00:12:49.450 --> 00:12:53.910
Every time he shows up,
the passengers freak out!

202
00:12:53.910 --> 00:12:55.800
So that's what he's doing...

203
00:12:55.800 --> 00:12:57.710
Okay, then! I won't eat him!

204
00:12:57.710 --> 00:12:59.440
I can't eat a fighter!

205
00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:01.800
Wanting to eat him was your first mistake!

206
00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:05.800
So, you guys headed somewhere?

207
00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:09.010
If you're gonna take
the sea train from here, there's:

208
00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:16.140
St. Poplar, Town of the Spring Queen...
Pucci, the Gourmet Town...

209
00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:18.860
and San Faldo, the Carnival Town!

210
00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:20.900
They're all fun places.

211
00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:25.820
If you work for the government,
you'd take a separate, special train.

212
00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:27.460
Okay, we'll pick the Gourmet Town.

213
00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:28.700
No, we won't!

214
00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:32.500
Since we've got our own ship,
we won't need the train.

215
00:13:32.500 --> 00:13:33.700
We can follow our log.

216
00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:35.750
Oh? Where's it pointing?

217
00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:37.540
Due east from here.

218
00:13:37.540 --> 00:13:41.460
So I see... That would be
none other than Water Seven.

219
00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:45.470
The train you saw earlier came
from that island's Blue Station.

220
00:13:46.430 --> 00:13:49.140
It's called the City of Water.
It's a real nice place.

221
00:13:49.140 --> 00:13:53.150
What's more, the city is known far and wide
for its shipbuilding industry.

222
00:13:53.150 --> 00:13:55.110
Their tech is the best in the world!

223
00:13:55.110 --> 00:14:00.000
Even the World Government favors
the ships built there! Amazing, right?

224
00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.090
Then... they've got some
awesome shipwrights, right?!

225
00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:09.490
Not just "some"! Only the world's
best shipwrights hang out there!

226
00:14:09.490 --> 00:14:10.540
Usopp!

227
00:14:10.540 --> 00:14:11.800
Yeah!

228
00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:13.600
Alright! I've decided!

229
00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:16.370
We'll go and get a shipwright
to join us for sure!

230
00:14:16.370 --> 00:14:20.360
Oh, is that right? Then hold on a sec.

231
00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:22.090
Up I go!

232
00:14:22.900 --> 00:14:25.170
What's she up to?

233
00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:25.170
Beats me.

234
00:14:25.170 --> 00:14:30.290
Well, then... Here's a basic map
of the island and a letter of introduction.

235
00:14:30.290 --> 00:14:35.600
Hand this to a guy named Iceburg
and ask him to fix up your ship real good.

236
00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:38.940
Water Seven is a big place. Don't get lost.

237
00:14:38.940 --> 00:14:40.130
Whoa!

238
00:14:40.130 --> 00:14:42.900
You have a heart of gold,
Miss Kokoro! You're so kind!

239
00:14:47.390 --> 00:14:50.910
In a bit, we're gonna go back
to Water Seven too.

240
00:14:50.910 --> 00:14:56.810
Oh, true! If we meet again,
first round's on me at my favorite bar.

241
00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:00.170
Okay! I hope we see you guys again!

242
00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:05.090
At Water Seven, it'll take about a week
for the log to register, so kick back and relax.

243
00:15:06.260 --> 00:15:08.510
Yeah! Thanks!

244
00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:13.400
All right, guys! Get ready to set sail!

245
00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:14.180
– Yeah!
– Yeah!

246
00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:15.200
Well then, we're off!

247
00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:18.560
Thanks for all your help,
Miss Kokoro and Chimney!

248
00:15:24.800 --> 00:15:26.650
Be careful!

249
00:15:28.820 --> 00:15:32.030
Watch out for the government people!

250
00:15:32.030 --> 00:15:34.950
Yahoo! Let's go!

251
00:15:34.950 --> 00:15:37.620
To the city of meat! Yahoo!

252
00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:39.580
Were you even listening?

253
00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:51.690
Mmm. What a nice breeze!

254
00:15:51.690 --> 00:15:54.500
Maybe we'll reach the City of Water
sooner than expected.

255
00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:55.850
I hope so.

256
00:15:56.310 --> 00:16:01.260
Luffy, leave scouting out the shipwright to me.
I'll find us an incredibly gorgeous woman.

257
00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:03.210
Don't be dumb! We need a shipwright!

258
00:16:03.210 --> 00:16:06.900
It's gotta be a big guy
the size of a mountain! Five meters tall!

259
00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:11.490
But if he's too big,
he might not fit on this ship.

260
00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:14.090
All that matters is that he's skilled, right?

261
00:16:14.090 --> 00:16:18.490
The real question is if there's someone
crazy enough to want to be on a pirate ship.

262
00:16:18.490 --> 00:16:22.330
I can't wait! We're gonna make a new friend!

263
00:16:22.330 --> 00:16:26.340
We were lucky to stop at the station first
since they drew a map for us.

264
00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:30.170
If we go to the place on the map
and find that Iceburg guy...

265
00:16:30.170 --> 00:16:32.380
<b>Around here</b>
<b>Water 7</b>

266
00:16:31.470 --> 00:16:32.380
Oh, okay.

267
00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:34.260
This tells me nothing!

268
00:16:35.010 --> 00:16:36.510
Whoa! This is like Luffy's art.

269
00:16:36.510 --> 00:16:39.720
<b>Shipwright</b>
<b>meters</b>
Here. We need to keep
an eye out for a guy like this.

270
00:16:40.350 --> 00:16:42.090
I'd run if I saw a guy like that.

271
00:16:42.090 --> 00:16:45.680
Same here. I'd hop on the next ship
and hightail it out to sea.

272
00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:49.410
But a thug like this might chase me
into open water like an octopus.

273
00:16:49.410 --> 00:16:51.240
What are you guys jabbering about?

274
00:16:51.240 --> 00:16:52.700
Come here, guys!

275
00:16:52.700 --> 00:16:55.870
I'll give you an allowance
for the week we're ashore.

276
00:16:55.870 --> 00:16:57.520
Seriously?! Yay! I'm first!

277
00:16:57.520 --> 00:16:59.240
Whoa! That's generous!

278
00:16:59.240 --> 00:17:01.750
Hey! Get in line!

279
00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:05.710
– Allowance! Allowance! Allowance!
– Allowance! Allowance! Allowance!

280
00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:17.600
You doing okay, Usopp?

281
00:17:17.600 --> 00:17:22.890
This tinplate patchwork brings back
memories of battles and adventure.

282
00:17:22.890 --> 00:17:27.810
I can't help but gush over
the thought of her upcoming repairs.

283
00:17:27.810 --> 00:17:29.650
I get it, but...

284
00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:29.650
Huh?

285
00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:34.860
our journey—especially since we entered
the Grand Line—has taken quite a toll on the Merry.

286
00:17:34.860 --> 00:17:38.410
The deck creaks, and the ship's
bottom is pretty leaky.

287
00:17:38.410 --> 00:17:41.950
If nothing's done, that'll be it
for both the ship and us.

288
00:17:41.950 --> 00:17:44.950
Yeah, but we're filthy rich now.

289
00:17:44.950 --> 00:17:48.500
We can make her good as new!
And more powerful, too!

290
00:17:49.260 --> 00:17:50.900
Yeah! More cannons!

291
00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:52.580
Also, a bronze statue!

292
00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:54.890
Hey, is that it?

293
00:17:54.890 --> 00:17:55.760
– Huh?
– Huh?

294
00:17:57.930 --> 00:18:01.740
It's the island! We can see the island!

295
00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:05.090
Okay, guys! Row!

296
00:18:05.090 --> 00:18:08.020
We've got a decent tailwind.
We shouldn't waste energy!

297
00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:19.410
How wonderful!

298
00:18:21.700 --> 00:18:22.740
It's incredible!

299
00:18:24.200 --> 00:18:29.080
<b>Water Seven
"The City of Water"
Grand Line</b>

300
00:18:28.010 --> 00:18:30.370
What is this place?!

301
00:18:39.590 --> 00:18:41.800
The fountain's enormous!

302
00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:45.720
Unbelievable! An actual industrial city!

303
00:18:45.720 --> 00:18:47.430
That's why it has the sea train.

304
00:18:47.430 --> 00:18:49.600
That must be the station in front.

305
00:18:50.410 --> 00:18:52.600
It says "Blue Station."

306
00:18:54.130 --> 00:18:55.610
I wonder where we dock.

307
00:18:55.610 --> 00:18:56.940
In town somewhere?

308
00:18:57.690 --> 00:19:00.200
Hey, you there!

309
00:18:59.610 --> 00:19:00.200
Hm?

310
00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:03.600
Pirates shouldn't openly sail out in front.

311
00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:05.790
Go around to the Backstreets!

312
00:19:06.810 --> 00:19:09.250
Okay! Thanks!

313
00:19:14.750 --> 00:19:17.710
Whoa, this is amazing! A city on the water?!

314
00:19:17.710 --> 00:19:21.590
Wow! This place is cool! Such a pretty city!

315
00:19:29.940 --> 00:19:34.940
But the city is flooded.
The houses are submerged in the sea.

316
00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:36.270
Look again.

317
00:19:36.270 --> 00:19:39.860
The city was designed
with its base underwater.

318
00:19:39.860 --> 00:19:42.320
You can see the foundation underneath.

319
00:19:43.090 --> 00:19:45.530
Oh, true! The pillars raise the structures!

320
00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:48.160
I see... That's why it's called
the City of Water, huh?

321
00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:51.120
Hey, hurry up and dock the ship!

322
00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.920
Hey, listen up, you guys!
Pirate ships should steer clear of this area!

323
00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:00.450
Did you come here to plunder?

324
00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:03.080
No! We wanna get our ship repaired!

325
00:20:03.080 --> 00:20:05.390
People just up and ask
if we're gonna plunder...?

326
00:20:05.390 --> 00:20:10.380
In that case, there's a cape just ahead,
so anchor your ship there for now!

327
00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:11.980
Okay!

328
00:20:11.980 --> 00:20:13.500
Thanks!

329
00:20:13.500 --> 00:20:14.810
Again?

330
00:20:14.810 --> 00:20:17.520
What'd you expect? We're pirates, after all.

331
00:20:19.540 --> 00:20:21.600
This spot's okay, right?

332
00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:25.210
It sure is bleak though.

333
00:20:25.210 --> 00:20:27.770
All right, then! Furl the sail!

334
00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:36.750
What're you doing?!

335
00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:39.840
Nothing! All I did was pull the rope!

336
00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:47.510
You're kidding me!
The Going Merry has gotten this rickety?

337
00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:52.350
Anyway, why aren't the people
on this island scared of pirates?

338
00:20:52.350 --> 00:20:55.620
Pirates probably come here for ships too.

339
00:20:55.620 --> 00:20:58.110
Less talking! More fixing!

340
00:20:58.110 --> 00:21:03.340
Maybe they have sentries strong enough
to deal with pirates who cause a ruckus?

341
00:21:03.340 --> 00:21:06.780
They probably do,
considering the size of the city.

342
00:21:06.780 --> 00:21:10.360
Is that so?! Then what're we
gonna do? This is bad.

343
00:21:10.360 --> 00:21:12.790
Why would it be bad? We're customers.

344
00:21:12.790 --> 00:21:14.120
Y-You think so?

345
00:21:14.120 --> 00:21:15.680
Okay, then! See you later!

346
00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:17.730
Wait, Luffy and Usopp!

347
00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:21.390
You two, come with me.

348
00:21:21.390 --> 00:21:22.380
– Hm?
– Hm?

349
00:21:24.010 --> 00:21:25.100
Come with you where?

350
00:21:25.100 --> 00:21:29.970
First, we'll take Miss Kokoro's letter of introduction
and go find the man named Iceburg.

351
00:21:29.970 --> 00:21:33.700
We'll ask him to facilitate the ship's repair.

352
00:21:33.700 --> 00:21:37.060
Then we have to find a place
where we can cash in our gold.

353
00:21:37.060 --> 00:21:42.570
If that's it, then okay!
Onward! To the City of Water!

354
00:21:42.570 --> 00:21:44.690
You're forgetting the gold.

355
00:21:44.690 --> 00:21:45.900
Ah...

356
00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:50.360
Hey! Some pirates are
raising hell at Dock One!

357
00:21:50.360 --> 00:21:51.870
What?! For real?!

358
00:21:51.870 --> 00:21:54.580
We'd better hurry and see!

359
00:21:55.540 --> 00:21:58.070
I don't understand what you're talking about.

360
00:21:55.620 --> 00:21:59.500
<b>A Shipyard
Water Seven</b>

361
00:21:58.070 --> 00:22:00.230
Well, actually...

362
00:21:59.580 --> 00:22:03.510
<b>Dock One</b>

363
00:22:03.510 --> 00:22:06.200
I thought about it carefully.

364
00:22:03.590 --> 00:22:09.090
<b>Captain Mikazuki
Big Helmet Pirates
Bounty: ¬36 Million</b>

365
00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:09.310
I thought about it really carefully.

366
00:22:09.310 --> 00:22:12.300
While it's true that you guys repaired our ship,

367
00:22:12.300 --> 00:22:16.960
I couldn't help but notice
the invoice was a bit too high.

368
00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:20.360
You're interrupting our work.

369
00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:25.060
So... I decided not to pay—not one belly.

370
00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:29.500
Thanks for the flawless repairs!

371
00:22:31.240 --> 00:22:33.290
Plus, it's all free!

372
00:22:44.710 --> 00:22:47.600
Well, Kalifa, what's going on over there?

373
00:22:47.600 --> 00:22:50.680
You see, Mr. Iceburg,
they're customers of Dock One.

374
00:22:50.680 --> 00:22:53.490
The repairs are complete,
but they refuse to pay.

375
00:22:54.140 --> 00:22:56.000
That's sexual harassment.

376
00:22:56.600 --> 00:22:59.560
Well... I suppose that is sexual harassment.

377
00:23:10.540 --> 00:23:14.240
Sir, you'd be wise not to
provoke craftsmen like that.

378
00:23:25.560 --> 00:23:27.460
B-Boss!

379
00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:29.470
– Boss!
– Boss!

380
00:23:30.270 --> 00:23:31.430
Oh, pardon me.

381
00:23:31.430 --> 00:23:36.510
You son of a bitch!
You should watch where you're going!

382
00:23:38.480 --> 00:23:40.440
Oh, pardon me.

383
00:23:40.440 --> 00:23:45.400
Y-You bastards! Are you picking a fight?!
Just who do you think we are?!

384
00:23:55.160 --> 00:23:58.790
Hey, have you test-fired the cannon?

385
00:23:58.790 --> 00:24:00.540
Oh, not yet, sir.

386
00:24:03.460 --> 00:24:07.460
Dammit! Who the hell are you guys?!

387
00:24:07.910 --> 00:24:10.920
We'll remember this!

388
00:24:23.350 --> 00:24:28.860
<b>Galley-La Company
A Shipbuilding Firm, Water Seven
(Purveyors to the World Government)</b>

389
00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:25.500
The pirate way of doing things

390
00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:28.860
doesn't work on craftsmen's turf, now, does it?

391
00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:32.610
Should we go to the exchange shop first?

392
00:24:32.610 --> 00:24:35.170
Why? Let's go to the shipyard.

393
00:24:35.170 --> 00:24:40.700
But we can't just walk around the island
with this much gold. It puts me on edge.

394
00:24:40.700 --> 00:24:43.160
Isn't it worth the same after it's exchanged?

395
00:24:43.160 --> 00:24:46.830
Even so, the size of our load
might attract attention, don't you think?

396
00:24:46.830 --> 00:24:48.730
What if we run into no good thieves?

397
00:24:48.730 --> 00:24:50.380
But we're thieves too!

398
00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:54.720
He's got a point. Trading it in for bills
would mean we each hold on to some of it.

399
00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:57.680
Hey, what's with that remark?

400
00:24:57.680 --> 00:25:00.000
Is there a problem
if I'm the one carrying it?

401
00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.510
Yeah. You might drop it or lose it somewhere.

402
00:25:02.510 --> 00:25:04.730
Yeah, he would. It's Luffy after all.

403
00:25:04.730 --> 00:25:07.610
What?! Guys! Don't you trust me?!

404
00:25:07.610 --> 00:25:08.360
– Nope!
– Nope!

405
00:25:09.570 --> 00:25:13.530
That really hurts! I might not recover from thi–

406
00:25:13.530 --> 00:25:14.200
Hm?

407
00:25:14.900 --> 00:25:18.490
Is this the only entrance to the city?

408
00:25:19.490 --> 00:25:21.050
A rental bull shop?

409
00:25:21.050 --> 00:25:22.120
What's that?

410
00:25:22.120 --> 00:25:24.290
What do they rent out?

411
00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:25.630
What's a "bull"?

412
00:25:25.710 --> 00:25:27.840
Beats me. Bulldogs?

413
00:25:28.720 --> 00:25:30.000
Can't be, right?

414
00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.520
Excuse me! We'd like to rent some bulls!

415
00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:34.220
Ask what they are first!

416
00:25:35.420 --> 00:25:38.390
Welcome! Here to rent bulls,
right? For how many?

417
00:25:38.390 --> 00:25:39.510
Three of us!

418
00:25:39.510 --> 00:25:41.500
What kind of bulls would you like?

419
00:25:41.500 --> 00:25:44.180
There are three classes:
yagara, rabuka, and king.

420
00:25:44.180 --> 00:25:47.320
Well, for the three of you,
two yagaras would probably do.

421
00:25:47.320 --> 00:25:49.150
Okay, roast 'em nice and tasty!

422
00:25:49.150 --> 00:25:50.980
Don't say weird things, you weirdo!

423
00:25:51.700 --> 00:25:54.440
Oh? Your log pose led you here?

424
00:25:54.440 --> 00:25:55.160
Yep.

425
00:25:55.160 --> 00:25:57.390
That's quite the undertaking, you guys.

426
00:25:57.390 --> 00:25:59.700
Then you had no idea
what bulls were, did you?

427
00:25:59.700 --> 00:26:00.750
– Right.
– Right.

428
00:26:00.750 --> 00:26:03.290
Well, long story short, those are bulls.

429
00:26:03.290 --> 00:26:05.960
Yagara bulls. You'll see them all over town.

430
00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:10.240
In this area, there's a fish called a yagara
that swims with its head out.

431
00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:13.960
This is the City of Water.
There are more canals than walkways.

432
00:26:13.960 --> 00:26:17.590
The residents here see bulls
as a necessary form of transportation.

433
00:26:18.300 --> 00:26:20.760
Same goes for any sightseeing on the island.

434
00:26:20.760 --> 00:26:22.820
That fish is pulling a boat?

435
00:26:22.820 --> 00:26:25.430
Actually, they let people ride on their backs.

436
00:26:25.430 --> 00:26:29.650
Well, it's like horseback riding
or riding in a carriage on land.

437
00:26:29.650 --> 00:26:31.610
In we go!

438
00:26:31.610 --> 00:26:35.650
You see the fish pen there?
Well, try and ride on one. It's comfortable.

439
00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:40.260
For a couple of two-passenger
yagara bulls, it'll be 2,000 belly, all told.

440
00:26:40.260 --> 00:26:41.740
Wow, they're cute!

441
00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.410
It's a fish that looks like a horse.

442
00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:49.500
You jerk! What'd you do that for?!

443
00:26:49.500 --> 00:26:52.840
Oh? He must like you.
Let's get that one for you.

444
00:26:59.180 --> 00:27:01.390
Can he carry heavy stuff okay?

445
00:27:01.390 --> 00:27:05.310
Their power is incredible! They're often used
when moving household goods.

446
00:27:05.950 --> 00:27:08.250
Quite the bag, huh? Whatcha got in there?

447
00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:09.350
Gold.

448
00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:13.230
Good one! Whatever it is, they can handle it.

449
00:27:13.230 --> 00:27:13.860
See?

450
00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:16.030
Whoa! Gimme!

451
00:27:15.040 --> 00:27:16.040
No way!

452
00:27:16.040 --> 00:27:18.030
This guy's awfully honest.

453
00:27:18.030 --> 00:27:20.700
And you! Don't show it off
to others so casually!

454
00:27:20.700 --> 00:27:22.690
Why's that? It's no big deal.

455
00:27:22.690 --> 00:27:24.740
My... That was a surprise.

456
00:27:24.740 --> 00:27:28.720
Well, then... It'll be a million belly
for two yagara bulls.

457
00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:30.580
Hey, the price went up, pops.

458
00:27:30.580 --> 00:27:33.330
Oh, right, are there any
exchange shops around here?

459
00:27:33.330 --> 00:27:40.400
Yeah, there are, but with that amount of gold,
the shops here probably won't have enough money.

460
00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:42.890
You should go downtown on Shipyard Island.

461
00:27:42.890 --> 00:27:46.720
Downtown Shipyard Island? Where's that?

462
00:27:46.720 --> 00:27:50.000
In that direction. Take this with you.

463
00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:51.270
A map?! Aha!

464
00:27:52.010 --> 00:27:53.440
This'll be helpful! Thanks!

465
00:27:53.440 --> 00:27:56.380
Pops, is the shipyard that way, too?

466
00:27:56.380 --> 00:27:58.810
Yeah. The world's number one shipyard!

467
00:27:58.810 --> 00:28:02.950
Perfect! Once we get the money,
we'll be real close to the shipyard.

468
00:28:02.950 --> 00:28:06.740
Yeah. We can finally have
the Going Merry repaired!

469
00:28:06.740 --> 00:28:10.540
And we'll find a shipwright, too!
I'm getting excited!

470
00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:11.590
Well, then...

471
00:28:11.590 --> 00:28:12.460
Shall we?

472
00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:15.380
Alright! Go, yagara!

473
00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:20.630
Thanks for your business! Be careful!

474
00:28:20.630 --> 00:28:23.730
Full speed to the shipyard!

475
00:28:23.730 --> 00:28:26.150
Yahoo!
